{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"Renamed files appear in their own category and are not also counted as a deletion plus an addition.","required_reality_check_level":"System","justification":"This depends on real git rename detection and status/diff semantics from an actual repository (subprocess + filesystem). Unit parsing tests can miss cases where git reports rename metadata differently, which would misclassify into add/delete buckets.","test_description":"Create a real temp git repo, commit baseline file, rename it with `git mv`, run the CLI against real git state, and assert stdout report includes the file only in `renamed` and not in `added`/`deleted`.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.18,"System":0.8,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"Diffs that include binary files do not cause the tool to crash; binary files are counted in the output.","required_reality_check_level":"System","justification":"Binary diff behavior is tied to real git subprocess output and real file content handling/encoding edges. Mocks can hide crash modes caused by real binary patch metadata or byte sequences.","test_description":"In a real temp repo, add/modify a binary file (e.g., random bytes), run the CLI, assert process exits successfully and report count includes the binary change.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.13,"System":0.85,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"Running the tool on a repository that has no commits yet produces an empty report rather than an error.","required_reality_check_level":"System","justification":"The failure mode comes from real git behavior in an unborn-HEAD repo (real subprocess error/exit semantics). Unit tests with mocked git responses can miss real command failures and stderr/exit-code handling.","test_description":"Initialize a new git repo with no commits